<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-212-142 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 360 430</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  March 1991 v2 n3 p49(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mail-order nugget. (Q Safety's earthquake-protection products)(Forum)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Feldman, Saul D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Q Sales (Products).andO;Topic:     EarthquakesComputer AccessoriesMicrocomputersPeripherals.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MAIL-ORDER NUGGET On October 17, 1989, at 5:04 p.m.andP;  (Pacific time),thousands of San Francisco residents sought shelter from a major earthquake.andO;As they scrambled for cover, many were unable to stop their PCs from tumblingoff their desks and onto the floor.andM;Regardless of where you live (and some seismologists are predicting temblorsfor areas around New York, St. Louis, and Seattle), you can't stop the earthfrom shaking.andP;  But you can take some precautions to ensure the safety of yourinvestment in high-technology computer equipment.andM;Q Safety (Q Sales, Pasadena, CA, 818-449-1950) sells a variety ofwell-designed products that will brace your PC, monitor, and printer in caseof an earthquake.andP;  Many of the products use Velcro Quake/Grip, a heavy-dutyfastening tape.andP;  Field tests during the San Francisco quake, which measured7.1 on the Richter scale, revealed that equipment secured with Quake/Gripsurvived unscathed.andM;Among the products in Q Safety's catalog are vertical braces ($46.95) thatattach your CPU to the side of your desk.andP;  Monitor fasteners ($7.95 to$17.95) attach your monitor to your desktop.andP;  These fasteners are speciallydesigned for specific types of monitors, including NEC MultiSync units onswivel stands ($14.95) and stationary monitors ($14.95).andP;  Products designedspecifically to protect laser printers ($17.95) and dot matrix printers($8.95) are available, and there's even a desk leash for your phone ($7.95).andO;Q Safety also offers volume discounts to corporate clients.andO;</TEXT></DOC>